"Latif M., Keenlyside N., Bader J.","Tropical sea surface temperature, vertical wind shear, and hurricane development",2007,"Geophysical Research Letters","34","1", L01710,"","",,,10.1029/2006GL027969,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34548035410&partnerID=40&md5=05e34f2bde25f09b55ff98a4f581ccac","Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, Duesternbrooker Weg 20, Kiel D-24105, Germany","Latif, M., Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, Duesternbrooker Weg 20, Kiel D-24105, Germany; Keenlyside, N., Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, Duesternbrooker Weg 20, Kiel D-24105, Germany; Bader, J., Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, Duesternbrooker Weg 20, Kiel D-24105, Germany","The anomalously strong hurricane activity in the Atlantic sector during the recent years led to a controversy about the impact of global warming on hurricane activity in the Atlantic sector. Here we show that the temperature difference between the tropical North Atlantic and the tropical Indian and Pacific Oceans (Indo-Pacific) is a key parameter in controlling the vertical wind shear over the Atlantic, an important quantity for hurricane activity. The stronger warming of the tropical North Atlantic relative to that of the Indo-Pacific during the most recent years drove reduced vertical wind shear over the Atlantic and is thus responsible for the strong hurricane activity observed. In 2006, however, the temperature difference between the tropical North Atlantic and the tropical Indian and Pacific Oceans is much reduced, which explains the relatively weak hurricane season. Copyright 2007 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Global warming; Wind; Wind stress; Indo-Pacific; Temperature difference; Tropical North Atlantic; Hurricanes; hurricane; sea surface temperature; temperature effect; tropical region; vertical movement; warming; wind shear; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (Tropical); Indian Ocean; Indian Ocean (Tropical); Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (Tropical)",,,,,,"Anthes, R.A., Hurricanes and global warming - Potential linkages and consequences (2006) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc, 87, pp. 623-628; Bader, J., Latif, M., The impact of decadal-scale Indian Ocean sea surface temperature anomalies on Sahelian rainfall and the North Atlantic Oscillation (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett, 30 (22), p. 2169. , doi:10.1029/2003GL018426; Emanuel, K., Increasing destructiveness of tropical cyclones over the past 30 years (2005) Nature, 436, pp. 686-688; Enfield, D.B., Mestas-Nuñez, A.M., Trimble, P.J., The Atlantic multidecadal oscillation and its relation to rainfall and river flows in the continental U.S (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett, 28, pp. 2077-2080; Giannini, A., Saravanan, R., Chang, P., Oceanic forcing of Sahel rainfall on interannual to interdecadal timescales (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1027-1030; Goldenberg, S.B., Shapiro, L.J., Physical mechanisms for the association of El Niño and West African rainfall with Atlantic major hurricane activity (1996) J. Clim, 9, pp. 1169-1187; Goldenberg, S.B., The recent increase in Atlantic hurricane activity: Causes and implications (2003) Science, 293, pp. 474-479; Kerr, R.A., Atlantic climate pacemaker for millennia past, decades hence? (2005) Science, 309, pp. 41-43; Knight, J.R., Allan, R.J., Folland, C.K., Vellinga, M., Mann, M.E., A signature of persistent natural thermohaline circulation cycles in observed climate (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett, 32, pp. L20709. , doi:10.1029/2005GL024233; Knight, J.R., Folland, C.K., Scaife, A.A., Climate impacts of the Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett, 33, pp. L17706. , doi:10.1029/2006GL026242; Landsea, C.W., Atlantic basin hurricanes: Indices of climate changes (1999) Clim. Change, 42, pp. 89-129; Latif, M., Is the thermohaline circulation changing? (2006) J. Clim, 19, pp. 4631-4637; Mann, M.E., Emanuel, K.A., Atlantic hurricane trends linked to climate change (2006) Eos Trans. AGU, 87 (24), p. 233; Pielke, R., et al. (2006), Reply to Hurricanes and global warming - Potential linkages and consequences, Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 87, 628-631Roeckner, E., The atmospheric general circulation model ECHAM5, part I: Model description, (2003), Rep. 323, Max Planck Inst. für Meteorol, Hamburg, GermanyTrenberth, K., Uncertainty in hurricanes and global warming (2005) Science, 308, pp. 1753-1754; Trenberth, K.E., Shea, D.J., Atlantic hurricanes and natural variability in 2005 (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett, 33, pp. L12704. , doi:10.1029/ 2006GL026894; Webster, P.J., Changes in tropical cyclone number, duration, and intensity in a warming environment (2005) Science, 309, pp. 1844-1846; Zhang, R., Delworth, T.L., Impact of Atlantic multidecadal oscillations on India/Sahel rainfall and Atlantic hurricanes (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett, 33, pp. L17712. , doi:10.1029/2006GL026267","Latif, M.; Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, Duesternbrooker Weg 20, Keil D-24105, Germany; email: mlatif@ifm-geomar.de",,,,,,,,00948276,,GPRLA,,"English","Geophys. Res. Lett.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-34548035410
